<dl id="n36082d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n36" href="#n36082d">N36 (VI.B.29)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n36all.htm#n36082d"> 82(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> swallows with lighted / sponges set fire to Dub-/lin thatches</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n36082d"><li>FW 542.21 </li><li><a href="../../flex/rB/lexrB.htm#n36082d">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/rB/l39rB.htm#n36082d">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n36082d">MS BL 47484b-443</ms> </li><li>JJA 59:83 <a name="rBd13" href="../../FF/fdra/rda.htm#rBd13">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/rB/rBd13.htm#n36082d">Draft: III&sect;3B.13</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">In the fanciful account of the historian Olaus Magnus, the city is said to have been taken by the unlikely stratagem of <mark>snaring a number of swallows and releasing them, each with a lighted sponge fastened under its wings, which speedily ignited the thatched roofs of the Irish town</mark>, and presently reduced it to ashes. <small> Samuel A. Ossory Fitzpatrick, <a name="SAOF" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#SAOF"><cite title="source">Dublin: A Historical and Topographical Account of the City</cite></a> (1907) 4</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: In text with German <i>Schwalbe</i>: swallow (bird); also, song <i>Hokey Pokey</i>. </mm> </dd></dl>
